echniques of legal comparison into an area of law where hitherto they have been little used. The jurisdictions most prominently featured are the mixed jurisdictions of Scotland and South Africa, but there are frequent comparative references, and special attention is given to the Netherlands as the country which has most recently re-written its succession law. The authors of the individual chapters are drawn from Scotland, South Africa, Germany, Italy and the Netherlands. Among the topics covered are freedom of testation, testamentary conditions and public policy, forfeiture clauses and events, revocation of wills by changed circumstances, revocation of mutual wills, fideicommissary substitutions, and succession agreements. The volume opens with an overview of the state of comparative law and with a consideration of compulsory heirship in Roman law.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2022) 4aLaw. 7aLAW / Comparative.2bisacsh1 aBarr, Alan R, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBraun, Alexandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChalmers, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErp, Sjef van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGretton, George L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHutchison, Dale, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaisley, Roderick R. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchoeman-Malan, M. C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSellar, W. David H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSonnekus, J. C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aToit, François du, econtributor.4ctb4https://id